<p><b>Area</b> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measure_(mat=
hematics)" title=3D"Measure (mathematics)">measure</a> of a <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domain_(mathematical_analysis)" title=3D"Domain (=
mathematical analysis)">region</a>'s size on a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Surface_(mathematics)" title=3D"Surface (mathematics)">surface=
</a>. The area of a plane region or <i>plane area</i> refers to the area of=
 a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shape" title=3D"Shape">shape</a=
> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planar_lamina" title=3D"Plana=
r lamina">planar lamina</a>, while <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Surface_area" title=3D"Surface area">surface area</a></i> refers to the=
 area of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Open_surface" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Open surface">open surface</a> or the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boundary_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Boundary (mathematics)">boundary</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Solid_geometry" title=3D"Solid geometry">three-dimensional o=
bject</a>. Area can be understood as the amount of material with a given th=
ickness that would be necessary to fashion a model of the shape, or the amo=
unt of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paint" title=3D"Paint">pain=
t</a> necessary to cover the surface with a single coat.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-MathWorld_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Area#cite_note-MathWorld-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It is the two-dimensional analogue=
 of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Length" title=3D"Length">l=
ength</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plane_curve" title=
=3D"Plane curve">curve</a> (a one-dimensional concept) or the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume" title=3D"Volume">volume</a> of a solid =
(a three-dimensional concept).
Two different regions may have the same area (as in <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Squaring_the_circle" title=3D"Squaring the circle">squari=
ng the circle</a>); by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Synecdoche"=
 title=3D"Synecdoche">synecdoche</a>, "area" sometimes is used to refer to =
the region, as in a "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polygonal_are=
a" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polygonal area">polygonal area</a>".
</p><p>The area of a shape can be measured by comparing the shape to <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square" title=3D"Square">squares</a> of =
a fixed size.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-AF_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-AF-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units" title=3D"I=
nternational System of Units">International System of Units</a> (SI), the s=
tandard unit of area is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square=
_metre" title=3D"Square metre">square metre</a> (written as m<sup>2</sup>),=
 which is the area of a square whose sides are one <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Metre" title=3D"Metre">metre</a> long.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
B_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#ci=
te_note-B-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup>  A shape with an area of three square metres would =
have the same area as three such squares.  In <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathematics">mathematics</a>, the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_square" title=3D"Unit square">unit s=
quare</a> is defined to have area one, and the area of any other shape or s=
urface is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimensionless_quantity=
" title=3D"Dimensionless quantity">dimensionless</a> <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real number</a>.
</p><p>There are several well-known <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Formula" title=3D"Formula">formulas</a> for the areas of simple shapes su=
ch as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle" title=3D"Triangle"=
>triangles</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rectangle" title=
=3D"Rectangle">rectangles</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Circle" title=3D"Circle">circles</a>.  Using these formulas, the area of a=
ny <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polygon" title=3D"Polygon">poly=
gon</a> can be found by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polygon_tr=
iangulation" title=3D"Polygon triangulation">dividing the polygon into tria=
ngles</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-bkos_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-bkos-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  For shapes wit=
h curved boundary, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus" title=
=3D"Calculus">calculus</a> is usually required to compute the area.  Indeed=
, the problem of determining the area of plane figures was a major motivati=
on for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_calculus" ti=
tle=3D"History of calculus">historical development of calculus</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Area#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For a solid shape such as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Sphere" title=3D"Sphere">sphere</a>, cone, or cylinder, the area of its bo=
undary surface is called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surfa=
ce_area" title=3D"Surface area">surface area</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MathWo=
rld_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#=
cite_note-MathWorld-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-MathWorldSurfaceArea_6=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_=
note-MathWorldSurfaceArea-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-7"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Formulas for the surface areas of simple shapes were computed by the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greek_mathematics" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Greek mathematics">ancient Greeks</a>, but computing the surfac=
e area of a more complicated shape usually requires <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Multivariable_calculus" title=3D"Multivariable calculus">=
multivariable calculus</a>.
</p><p>Area plays an important role in modern mathematics.  In addition to =
its obvious importance in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry=
" title=3D"Geometry">geometry</a> and calculus, area is related to the defi=
nition of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant" title=3D"De=
terminant">determinants</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lin=
ear_algebra" title=3D"Linear algebra">linear algebra</a>, and is a basic pr=
operty of surfaces in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential=
_geometry" title=3D"Differential geometry">differential geometry</a>.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-doCarmo_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-doCarmo-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Analysis" title=3D"Analysis">analysis</a>, the area of a=
 subset of the plane is defined using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Lebesgue_measure" title=3D"Lebesgue measure">Lebesgue measure</a>,<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-Rudin_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-Rudin-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> though not every subset is m=
easurable if one supposes the axiom of choice.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-10">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>  In general, area in higher mathematics is seen as a special ca=
se of volume for two-dimensional regions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MathWorld_1-2"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_not=
e-MathWorld-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Area can be defined through the use of axioms, defining it as a func=
tion of a collection of certain plane figures to the set of real numbers. I=
t can be proved that such a function exists.
</p>
