1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jordan_measure" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Jordan measure">Jordan measure</a></div>
<p>An approach to defining what is meant by "area" is through <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom" title=3D"Axiom">axioms</a>. "Area" can b=
e defined as a function from a collection M of a special kinds of plane fig=
ures (termed measurable sets) to the set of real numbers, which satisfies t=
he following properties:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Apostol_11-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-Apostol-11"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>For all <i>S</i> in <i>M</i>, <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>a</i>(<i>S<=
/i>) =E2=89=A5 0</span>.</li>
<li>If <i>S</i> and <i>T</i> are in <i>M</i> then so are <span class=3D"now=
rap"><i>S</i> =E2=88=AA <i>T</i></span> and <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>S</i>=
 =E2=88=A9 <i>T</i></span>, and also <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>a</i>(<i>S</=
i>=E2=88=AA<i>T</i>) =3D <i>a</i>(<i>S</i>) + <i>a</i>(<i>T</i>) =E2=88=92 =
<i>a</i>(<i>S</i> =E2=88=A9 <i>T</i>)</span>.</li>
<li>If <i>S</i> and <i>T</i> are in <i>M</i> with <span class=3D"nowrap"><i=
>S</i> =E2=8A=86 <i>T</i></span> then <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>T</i> =E2=
=88=92 <i>S</i></span> is in <i>M</i> and <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>a</i>(<=
i>T</i>=E2=88=92<i>S</i>) =3D <i>a</i>(<i>T</i>) =E2=88=92 <i>a</i>(<i>S</i=
>)</span>.</li>
<li>If a set <i>S</i> is in <i>M</i> and <i>S</i> is congruent to <i>T</i> =
then <i>T</i> is also in <i>M</i> and <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>a</i>(<i>S<=
/i>) =3D <i>a</i>(<i>T</i>)</span>.</li>
<li>Every rectangle <i>R</i> is in <i>M</i>. If the rectangle has length <i=
>h</i> and breadth <i>k</i> then <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>a</i>(<i>R</i>) =
=3D <i>hk</i></span>.</li>
<li>Let <i>Q</i> be a set enclosed between two step regions <i>S</i> and <i=
>T</i>. A step region is formed from a finite union of adjacent rectangles =
resting on a common base, i.e. <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>S</i> =E2=8A=86 <i=
>Q</i> =E2=8A=86 <i>T</i></span>. If there is a unique number <i>c</i> such=
 that <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>a</i>(<i>S</i>) =E2=89=A4 c =E2=89=A4 <i>a<=
/i>(<i>T</i>)</span> for all such step regions <i>S</i> and <i>T</i>, then =
<span class=3D"nowrap"><i>a</i>(<i>Q</i>) =3D <i>c</i></span>.</li></ul>
<p>It can be proved that such an area function actually exists.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-Moise_12-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Area#cite_note-Moise-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Units">Units</h2><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArea&amp;action=3Dedit&amp=
;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Units"><span>edit</span></a><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:SquareMeterQuadrat.JPG" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"A square made of PVC pipe on grass" sr=
c=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ef/SquareMeterQ=
uadrat.JPG/250px-SquareMeterQuadrat.JPG" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" h=
eight=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2048" data-file-=
height=3D"1536"></a><figcaption>A square metre <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Quadrat" title=3D"Quadrat">quadrat</a> made of PVC pipe</figca=
ption></figure>
<p>Every <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_of_length" title=3D"=
Unit of length">unit of length</a> has a corresponding unit of area, namely=
 the area of a square with the given side length.  Thus areas can be measur=
ed in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_metre" title=3D"Squar=
e metre">square metres</a> (m<sup>2</sup>), square centimetres (cm<sup>2</s=
up>), square millimetres (mm<sup>2</sup>), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Square_kilometre" title=3D"Square kilometre">square kilometres</a>=
 (km<sup>2</sup>), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_foot" ti=
tle=3D"Square foot">square feet</a> (ft<sup>2</sup>), <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_yard" title=3D"Square yard">square yards</a> (yd=
<sup>2</sup>), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_mile" title=
=3D"Square mile">square miles</a> (mi<sup>2</sup>), and so forth.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-BIPM2006Ch5_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-BIPM2006Ch5-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  Algebraically, th=
ese units can be thought of as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Square_(algebra)" title=3D"Square (algebra)">squares</a> of the correspond=
ing length units.
</p><p>The SI unit of area is the square metre, which is considered an <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_derived_unit" title=3D"SI derived u=
nit">SI derived unit</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-B_3-1" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-B-3"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Conversions">Conversions</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArea&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Conversions"><span>edit</s=
pan></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Area_conversion_-_square_mm_i=
n_a_square_cm.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"A diagram show=
ing the conversion factor between different areas" src=3D"https://upload.wi=
kimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/Area_conversion_-_square_mm_in_a_s=
quare_cm.png/250px-Area_conversion_-_square_mm_in_a_square_cm.png" decoding=
=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"210" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file=
-width=3D"831" data-file-height=3D"699"></a><figcaption>Although there are =
10 mm in 1 cm, there are 100 mm<sup>2</sup> in 1 cm<sup>2</sup>.</figcaptio=
n></figure>
<p>Calculation of the area of a square whose length and width are 1 metre w=
ould be:
</p><p>1 metre =C3=97 1 metre =3D 1&nbsp;m<sup>2</sup>
</p><p>and so, a rectangle with different sides (say length of 3 metres and=
 width of 2 metres) would have an area in square units that can be calculat=
ed as:
</p><p>3 metres =C3=97 2 metres =3D 6&nbsp;m<sup>2</sup>. This is equivalen=
t to 6 million square millimetres. Other useful conversions are:
</p>
<ul><li>1 square kilometre =3D <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mil=
lion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Million">1,000,000</a> square metres</=
li>
<li>1 square metre =3D <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/10000_(numb=
er)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"10000 (number)">10,000</a> square centi=
metres =3D 1,000,000 square millimetres</li>
<li>1 square centimetre =3D <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/100_(n=
umber)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"100 (number)">100</a> square millime=
tres.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Non-metric_units">Non-metri=
c units</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArea=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Non-metric units=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p>In non-metric units, the conversion between two square units is the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_(algebra)" title=3D"Square (alg=
ebra)">square</a> of the conversion between the corresponding length units.
</p>
<dl><dd>1 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foot_(unit)" title=3D"Fo=
ot (unit)">foot</a> =3D 12 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inch" t=
itle=3D"Inch">inches</a>,</dd></dl>
<p>the relationship between square feet and square inches is
</p>
<dl><dd>1 square foot =3D 144 square inches,</dd></dl>
<p>where 144 =3D 12<sup>2</sup> =3D 12 =C3=97 12.  Similarly:
</p>
<ul><li>1 square yard =3D <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/9_(numbe=
r)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"9 (number)">9</a> square feet</li>
<li>1 square mile =3D 3,097,600 square yards =3D 27,878,400 square feet</li=
></ul>
<p>In addition, conversion factors include:
</p>
<ul><li>1 square inch =3D 6.4516 square centimetres</li>
<li>1 square foot =3D <span style=3D"white-space:nowrap">0.092<span style=
=3D"margin-left:0.25em">903</span><span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em">04</sp=
an></span> square metres</li>
<li>1 square yard =3D <span style=3D"white-space:nowrap">0.836<span style=
=3D"margin-left:0.25em">127</span><span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em">36</sp=
an></span> square metres</li>
<li>1 square mile =3D <span style=3D"white-space:nowrap">2.589<span style=
=3D"margin-left:0.25em">988</span><span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em">110</s=
pan><span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em">336</span></span> square kilometres<=
/li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other_units_including_histo=
rical">Other units including historical</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArea&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=
=3D"Edit section: Other units including historical"><span>edit</span></a><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Category:Units_of_area" =
title=3D"Category:Units of area">Category:Units of area</a></div>
<p>There are several other common units for area.  The <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Are_(unit)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Are (unit)"=
>are</a> was the original unit of area in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Metric_system" title=3D"Metric system">metric system</a>, with:
</p>
<ul><li>1 are =3D 100 square metres</li></ul>
<p>Though the are has fallen out of use, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Hectare" title=3D"Hectare">hectare</a> is still commonly used to=
 measure land:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-BIPM2006Ch5_13-1" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-BIPM2006Ch5-13"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p>
<ul><li>1 hectare =3D 100 ares =3D 10,000 square metres =3D 0.01 square kil=
ometres</li></ul>
<p>Other uncommon metric units of area include the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Tetrad_(unit_of_area)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tetr=
ad (unit of area)">tetrad</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Hectad" title=3D"Hectad">hectad</a>, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Myriad_(area)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Myriad (area)">my=
riad</a>.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acre" title=3D"Acre">ac=
re</a> is also commonly used to measure land areas, where
</p>
<ul><li>1 acre =3D 4,840 square yards =3D 43,560 square feet.</li></ul>
<p>An acre is approximately 40% of a hectare.
</p><p>On the atomic scale, area is measured in units of <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barn_(unit)" title=3D"Barn (unit)">barns</a>, such t=
hat:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-BIPM2006Ch5_13-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-BIPM2006Ch5-13"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>1 barn =3D 10<sup>=E2=88=9228</sup> square meters.</li></ul>
<p>The barn is commonly used in describing the cross-sectional area of inte=
raction in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_physics" title=
=3D"Nuclear physics">nuclear physics</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-BIPM2006Ch5_13=
-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_=
note-BIPM2006Ch5-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Asia" title=3D"Sou=
th Asia">South Asia</a> (mainly Indians), although the countries use SI uni=
ts as official, many South Asians still use traditional units. Each adminis=
trative division has its own area unit, some of them have same names, but w=
ith different values. There's no official consensus about the traditional u=
nits values. Thus, the conversions between the SI units and the traditional=
 units may have different results, depending on what reference that has bee=
n used.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-15"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-17"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_not=
e-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Some traditional South Asian units that have fixed value:
</p>
<ul><li>1 Killa =3D 1 acre</li>
<li>1 Ghumaon =3D 1 acre</li>
<li>1 Kanal =3D 0.125 acre (1 acre =3D 8 kanal)</li>
<li>1 Decimal =3D 48.4 square yards</li>
<li>1 Chatak =3D 180 square feet</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArea&amp;action=3Dedit=
&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Circle_area">Circle area</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArea&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Circle area"><span>edit</s=
pan></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area_of_a_circle#His=
tory" title=3D"Area of a circle">Area of a circle =C2=A7&nbsp;History</a></=
div>
<p>In the 5th century BCE, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hippocr=
ates_of_Chios" title=3D"Hippocrates of Chios">Hippocrates of Chios</a> was =
the first to show that the area of a disk (the region enclosed by a circle)=
 is proportional to the square of its diameter, as part of his <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadrature_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Quadrature (geometry)">quadrature</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Lune_of_Hippocrates" title=3D"Lune of Hippocrates">lune =
of Hippocrates</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-heath_18-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-heath-18"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 but did not identify the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constant=
_of_proportionality" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Constant of proportiona=
lity">constant of proportionality</a>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Eudoxus_of_Cnidus" title=3D"Eudoxus of Cnidus">Eudoxus of Cnidus</a>, =
also in the 5th century BCE, also found that the area of a disk is proporti=
onal to its radius squared.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Subsequently, Book I of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euc=
lid%27s_Elements" title=3D"Euclid's Elements">Euclid's <i>Elements</i></a> =
dealt with equality of areas between two-dimensional figures. The mathemati=
cian <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archimedes" title=3D"Archimed=
es">Archimedes</a> used the tools of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Euclidean_geometry" title=3D"Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</a> =
to show that the area inside a circle is equal to that of a <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right_triangle" title=3D"Right triangle">right tr=
iangle</a> whose base has the length of the circle's circumference and whos=
e height equals the circle's radius, in his book <i><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Measurement_of_a_Circle" title=3D"Measurement of a Circle=
">Measurement of a Circle</a></i>. (The circumference is 2<span class=3D"te=
xhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span><i>r</i>, and the are=
a of a triangle is half the base times the height, yielding the area <span =
class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span><i>r</i><s=
up>2</sup> for the disk.) Archimedes approximated the value of <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span> (and hence the=
 area of a unit-radius circle) with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Area_of_a_disk#Archimedes'_doubling_method" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Area of a disk">his doubling method</a>, in which he inscribed a regula=
r triangle in a circle and noted its area, then doubled the number of sides=
 to give a regular <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hexagon" title=
=3D"Hexagon">hexagon</a>, then repeatedly doubled the number of sides as th=
e polygon's area got closer and closer to that of the circle (and did the s=
ame with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circumscribed_polygon" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Circumscribed polygon">circumscribed polygons<=
/a>).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Triangle_area">Triangle are=
a</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArea&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Triangle area"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"excerpt-block"><link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" hre=
f=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnot=
e navigation-not-searchable dablink excerpt-hat selfref">This section is an=
 excerpt from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area_of_a_triangle#H=
istory" title=3D"Area of a triangle">Area of a triangle =C2=A7 History</a>.=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-like plainlinks"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DArea_of_a_triangle&amp;action=3Dedit">edit</a><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div><div class=3D"excerp=
t">
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heron_of_Alexandria" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Heron of Alexandria">Heron of Alexandria</a> found wha=
t is known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heron%27s_formula" t=
itle=3D"Heron's formula">Heron's formula</a> for the area of a triangle in =
terms of its sides, and a proof can be found in his book, <i>Metrica</i>, w=
ritten around 60 CE. It has been suggested that <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Archimedes" title=3D"Archimedes">Archimedes</a> knew the form=
ula over two centuries earlier,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and=
 since <i>Metrica</i> is a collection of the mathematical knowledge availab=
le in the ancient world, it is possible that the formula predates the refer=
ence given in that work.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In 300 BCE=
 Greek mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid" title=
=3D"Euclid">Euclid</a> proved that the area of a triangle is half that of a=
 parallelogram with the same base and height in his book <i>Elements of Geo=
metry</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 499 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aryabhata" title=3D"=
Aryabhata">Aryabhata</a>, a great <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Mathematician" title=3D"Mathematician">mathematician</a>-<a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astronomer" title=3D"Astronomer">astronomer</a> from=
 the classical age of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_mathe=
matics" title=3D"Indian mathematics">Indian mathematics</a> and <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_astronomy" title=3D"Indian astronomy">=
Indian astronomy</a>, expressed the area of a triangle as one-half the base=
 times the height in the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aryabh=
atiya" title=3D"Aryabhatiya">Aryabhatiya</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-2=
3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p>
A formula equivalent to Heron's was discovered by the Chinese independently=
 of the Greeks. It was published in 1247 in <i>Shushu Jiuzhang</i> ("<a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_Treatise_in_Nine_Sections" =
title=3D"Mathematical Treatise in Nine Sections">Mathematical Treatise in N=
ine Sections</a>"), written by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qin=
_Jiushao" title=3D"Qin Jiushao">Qin Jiushao</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-24=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup></div></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Quadrilateral_area">Quadril=
ateral area</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Area&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Quadrilatera=
l area"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span=
></span></div>
<p>In the 7th century CE, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brahmagu=
pta" title=3D"Brahmagupta">Brahmagupta</a> developed a formula, now known a=
s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brahmagupta%27s_formula" title=
=3D"Brahmagupta's formula">Brahmagupta's formula</a>, for the area of a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyclic_quadrilateral" title=3D"Cyclic=
 quadrilateral">cyclic quadrilateral</a> (a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Quadrilateral" title=3D"Quadrilateral">quadrilateral</a> <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inscribed_figure" title=3D"Inscribed figu=
re">inscribed</a> in a circle) in terms of its sides. In 1842, the German m=
athematicians <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Anton_Bretschne=
ider" title=3D"Carl Anton Bretschneider">Carl Anton Bretschneider</a> and <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Georg_Christian_von_Staudt" ti=
tle=3D"Karl Georg Christian von Staudt">Karl Georg Christian von Staudt</a>=
 independently found a formula, known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Bretschneider%27s_formula" title=3D"Bretschneider's formula">Bretsch=
neider's formula</a>, for the area of any quadrilateral.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"General_polygon_area">Gener=
al polygon area</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DArea&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: General=
 polygon area"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>The development of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian_co=
ordinate_system" title=3D"Cartesian coordinate system">Cartesian coordinate=
s</a> by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ren%C3%A9_Descartes" titl=
e=3D"Ren=C3=A9 Descartes">Ren=C3=A9 Descartes</a> in the 17th century allow=
ed the development of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shoelace=
_formula" title=3D"Shoelace formula">surveyor's formula</a> for the area of=
 any polygon with known <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertex_(ge=
ometry)" title=3D"Vertex (geometry)">vertex</a> locations by <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gauss" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gauss">Gau=
ss</a> in the 19th century.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Areas_determined_using_calc=
ulus">Areas determined using calculus</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DArea&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D=
"Edit section: Areas determined using calculus"><span>edit</span></a><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The development of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral_cal=
culus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Integral calculus">integral calculus<=
/a> in the late 17th century provided tools that could subsequently be used=
 for computing more complicated areas, such as the area of an <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellipse#Area" title=3D"Ellipse">ellipse</a> and=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_area" title=3D"Surfac=
e area">surface areas</a> of various curved three-dimensional objects.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Area_formulas">Area formula=
s</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArea&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Area formulas"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Polygon_formulas">Polygon f=
ormulas</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArea=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Polygon formula=
s"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
