<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Rectangles">Rectangles</h4>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArea&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Rectangles"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:RectangleLengthWidth.svg" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"A rectangle with length and width la=
belled" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8d/Re=
ctangleLengthWidth.svg/250px-RectangleLengthWidth.svg.png" decoding=3D"asyn=
c" width=3D"190" height=3D"147" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"220" data-file-height=3D"170"></a><figcaption>The area of this rectangl=
e is&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">lw</spa=
n>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The most basic area formula is the formula for the area of a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rectangle" title=3D"Rectangle">rectangle</a>.=
 Given a rectangle with length <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-s=
tyle:italic;">l</span> and width <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font=
-style:italic;">w</span>, the formula for the area is:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-A=
F_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#ci=
te_note-AF-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml texhtml-big" style=3D"font-size:165%;"><i>A<=
/i> =3D <i>lw</i></span> &nbsp;(rectangle).</dd></dl>
<p>That is, the area of the rectangle is the length multiplied by the width=
.  As a special case, as <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>l</i> =3D <i>w</i></spa=
n> in the case of a square, the area of a square with side length <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">s</span> is given by the f=
ormula:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MathWorld_1-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-MathWorld-1"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-AF_2-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Area#cite_note-AF-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml texhtml-big" style=3D"font-size:165%;"><i>A<=
/i> =3D <i>s</i><sup>2</sup></span> &nbsp;(square).</dd></dl>
<p>The formula for the area of a rectangle follows directly from the basic =
properties of area, and is sometimes taken as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Definition" title=3D"Definition">definition</a> or <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom" title=3D"Axiom">axiom</a>.  On the ot=
her hand, if <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry" title=3D"Ge=
ometry">geometry</a> is developed before <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Arithmetic" title=3D"Arithmetic">arithmetic</a>, this formula can be=
 used to define <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplication" ti=
tle=3D"Multiplication">multiplication</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real numbers</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Dissection,_parallelograms,=
_and_triangles"><span id=3D"Dissection.2C_parallelograms.2C_and_triangles">=
</span>Dissection, parallelograms, and triangles</h4><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArea&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1=
5" title=3D"Edit section: Dissection, parallelograms, and triangles"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle_area" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Triangle area">Triangle area</a> and <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelogram#Area_formula" title=3D"Parallel=
ogram">Parallelogram =C2=A7&nbsp;Area formula</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:ParallelogramArea.svg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/1/1c/ParallelogramArea.svg/250px-ParallelogramArea.svg.png" =
decoding=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=3D"250" class=3D"mw-file-element" d=
ata-file-width=3D"204" data-file-height=3D"268"></a><figcaption>A parallelo=
gram can be cut up and re-arranged to form a rectangle.</figcaption></figur=
e>
<p>Most other simple formulas for area follow from the method of <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dissection_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Dissection (geometry)">dissection</a>.
This involves cutting a shape into pieces, whose areas must <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Addition" title=3D"Addition">sum</a> to the area =
of the original shape.
For an example, any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelogram"=
 title=3D"Parallelogram">parallelogram</a> can be subdivided into a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid" title=3D"Trapezoid">trapezoid<=
/a> and a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right_triangle" title=3D=
"Right triangle">right triangle</a>, as shown in figure to the left.  If th=
e triangle is moved to the other side of the trapezoid, then the resulting =
figure is a rectangle.  It follows that the area of the parallelogram is th=
e same as the area of the rectangle:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-AF_2-3" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-AF-2"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml texhtml-big" style=3D"font-size:165%;"><i>A<=
/i> =3D <i>bh</i></span> &nbsp;(parallelogram).</dd></dl>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:TriangleArea.svg" class=3D"mw=
-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commo=
ns/thumb/7/7c/TriangleArea.svg/250px-TriangleArea.svg.png" decoding=3D"asyn=
c" width=3D"190" height=3D"138" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"220" data-file-height=3D"160"></a><figcaption>A parallelogram split int=
o two equal triangles</figcaption></figure>
<p>However, the same parallelogram can also be cut along a <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diagonal" title=3D"Diagonal">diagonal</a> into two=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congruence_(geometry)" title=3D"C=
ongruence (geometry)">congruent</a> triangles, as shown in the figure to th=
e right.  It follows that the area of each <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Triangle" title=3D"Triangle">triangle</a> is half the area of the =
parallelogram:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-AF_2-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-AF-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e A=3D{\frac {1}{2}}bh}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>A</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mn>1</mn>
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mi>b</mi>
        <mi>h</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle A=3D{\frac {1=
}{2}}bh}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/78bb1af1b9493a6b26955f711ae9b95a68f671be" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -1.838ex; width:9.177ex; height:5.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle A=
=3D{\frac {1}{2}}bh}"></span> &nbsp;(triangle).</dd></dl>
<p>Similar arguments can be used to find area formulas for the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid" title=3D"Trapezoid">trapezoid</a><s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Area#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> as well as more complicated <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polygon" title=3D"Polygon">polygons</a>.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Area#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Area_of_curved_shapes">Area=
 of curved shapes</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DArea&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: Area =
of curved shapes"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Circles">Circles</h4><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArea&amp;action=3Dedit=
&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Circles"><span>edit</span></a><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:CircleArea.svg" class=3D"mw-f=
ile-description"><img alt=3D"A circle divided into many sectors can be re-a=
rranged roughly to form a parallelogram" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.or=
g/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/CircleArea.svg/250px-CircleArea.svg.png" dec=
oding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"271" class=3D"mw-file-element" data=
-file-width=3D"240" data-file-height=3D"260"></a><figcaption>A circle can b=
e divided into <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circular_sector" ti=
tle=3D"Circular sector">sectors</a> which rearrange to form an approximate =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelogram" title=3D"Parallelog=
ram">parallelogram</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area_of_a_circle" ti=
tle=3D"Area of a circle">Area of a circle</a></div>
<p>The formula for the area of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
ircle" title=3D"Circle">circle</a> (more properly called the area enclosed =
by a circle or the area of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disk_=
(mathematics)" title=3D"Disk (mathematics)">disk</a>) is based on a similar=
 method.  Given a circle of radius <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i></span>,=
 it is possible to partition the circle into <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Circular_sector" title=3D"Circular sector">sectors</a>, as shown=
 in the figure to the right.  Each sector is approximately triangular in sh=
ape, and the sectors can be rearranged to form an approximate parallelogram=
.  The height of this parallelogram is <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i></sp=
an>, and the width is half the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cir=
cumference" title=3D"Circumference">circumference</a> of the circle, or <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml">=CF=80<i>r</i></span>.  Thus, the total area of the ci=
rcle is <span class=3D"texhtml">=CF=80<i>r</i><sup>2</sup></span>:<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-AF_2-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Area#cite_note-AF-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml texhtml-big" style=3D"font-size:165%;"><i>A<=
/i> =3D =CF=80<i>r</i><sup>2</sup></span> &nbsp;(circle).</dd></dl>
<p>Though the dissection used in this formula is only approximate, the erro=
r becomes smaller and smaller as the circle is partitioned into more and mo=
re sectors.  The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_(mathematic=
s)" title=3D"Limit (mathematics)">limit</a> of the areas of the approximate=
 parallelograms is exactly <span class=3D"texhtml">=CF=80<i>r</i><sup>2</su=
p></span>, which is the area of the circle.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Surveyor_28-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_n=
ote-Surveyor-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>This argument is actually a simple application of the ideas of <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus" title=3D"Calculus">calculus</=
a>.  In ancient times, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Method_=
of_exhaustion" title=3D"Method of exhaustion">method of exhaustion</a> was =
used in a similar way to find the area of the circle, and this method is no=
w recognized as a precursor to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Int=
egral_calculus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Integral calculus">integral =
calculus</a>.  Using modern methods, the area of a circle can be computed u=
sing a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Definite_integral" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Definite integral">definite integral</a>:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e A\;=3D\;2\int _{-r}^{r}{\sqrt {r^{2}-x^{2}}}\,dx\;=3D\;\pi r^{2}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>A</mi>
        <mspace width=3D"thickmathspace"></mspace>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mspace width=3D"thickmathspace"></mspace>
        <mn>2</mn>
        <msubsup>
          <mo>=E2=88=AB<!-- =E2=88=AB --></mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
            <mi>r</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>r</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msubsup>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <msup>
              <mi>r</mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>2</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msup>
            <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
            <msup>
              <mi>x</mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>2</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msup>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mspace width=3D"thickmathspace"></mspace>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mspace width=3D"thickmathspace"></mspace>
        <mi>=CF=80<!-- =CF=80 --></mi>
        <msup>
          <mi>r</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle A\;=3D\;2\int=
 _{-r}^{r}{\sqrt {r^{2}-x^{2}}}\,dx\;=3D\;\pi r^{2}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
