<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Non-planar_surface_area">No=
n-planar surface area</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DArea&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section: N=
on-planar surface area"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_area" title=
=3D"Surface area">Surface area</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Archimedes_sphere_and_cylinde=
r.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"A blue sphere inside a cyl=
inder of the same height and radius" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wi=
kipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/Archimedes_sphere_and_cylinder.svg/250px-Archime=
des_sphere_and_cylinder.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D=
"271" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"426" data-file-height=3D=
"461"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archimedes" =
title=3D"Archimedes">Archimedes</a> showed that the surface area of a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sphere" title=3D"Sphere">sphere</a> is =
exactly four times the area of a flat <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Disk_(mathematics)" title=3D"Disk (mathematics)">disk</a> of the same r=
adius, and the volume enclosed by the sphere is exactly 2/3 of the volume o=
f a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cylinder_(geometry)" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Cylinder (geometry)">cylinder</a> of the same height =
and radius.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Most basic formulas for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface=
_area" title=3D"Surface area">surface area</a> can be obtained by cutting s=
urfaces and flattening them out (see: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Developable_surface" title=3D"Developable surface">developable surfaces=
</a>).  For example, if the side surface of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Cylinder_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cylinder (g=
eometry)">cylinder</a> (or any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pri=
sm_(geometry)" title=3D"Prism (geometry)">prism</a>) is cut lengthwise, the=
 surface can be flattened out into a rectangle.  Similarly, if a cut is mad=
e along the side of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cone_(geomet=
ry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cone (geometry)">cone</a>, the side sur=
face can be flattened out into a sector of a circle, and the resulting area=
 computed.
</p><p>The formula for the surface area of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Sphere" title=3D"Sphere">sphere</a> is more difficult to derive:=
 because a sphere has nonzero <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaus=
sian_curvature" title=3D"Gaussian curvature">Gaussian curvature</a>, it can=
not be flattened out.  The formula for the surface area of a sphere was fir=
st obtained by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archimedes" title=
=3D"Archimedes">Archimedes</a> in his work <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/On_the_Sphere_and_Cylinder" title=3D"On the Sphere and Cylinder=
">On the Sphere and Cylinder</a></i>.  The formula is:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-M=
athWorldSurfaceArea_6-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-MathWorldSurfaceArea-6"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i> =3D 4<i>=CF=80r</i><sup>2</sup></s=
pan> &nbsp;(sphere),</dd></dl>
<p>where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i></span> is the radius of the spher=
e.  As with the formula for the area of a circle, any derivation of this fo=
rmula inherently uses methods similar to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Calculus" title=3D"Calculus">calculus</a>.
</p>
