                </mrow>
                <mo>]</mo>
              </mrow>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>2</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msup>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">d</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mi>x</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle A=3D2\pi \int=
 _{a}^{b}\!f(x){\sqrt {1+\left[f'(x)\right]^{2}}}\mathrm {d} x}</annotation=
>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/07cf6da325a77c650339de80d9b00d984ca3751d" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.338ex; width:31.983ex; height:6.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle A=
=3D2\pi \int _{a}^{b}\!f(x){\sqrt {1+\left[f'(x)\right]^{2}}}\mathrm {d} x}=
"></span><br>
<p>(rotation around the  x-axis)
</p>
</td>
<td><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:=
Vase-1-tab.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wi=
kimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/Vase-1-tab.svg/250px-Vase-1-tab.sv=
g.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"220" height=3D"117" class=3D"mw-file-ele=
ment" data-file-width=3D"396" data-file-height=3D"210"></a></span>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
<p>The above calculations show how to find the areas of many common <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shapes" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sh=
apes">shapes</a>.
</p><p>The areas of irregular (and thus arbitrary) polygons can be calculat=
ed using the "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surveyor%27s_formula=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Surveyor's formula">Surveyor's formula</a>=
" (shoelace formula).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Surveyor_28-1" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-Surveyor-28"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Relation_of_area_to_perimet=
er">Relation of area to perimeter</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DArea&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edi=
t section: Relation of area to perimeter"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isoperimetric_inequality" t=
itle=3D"Isoperimetric inequality">isoperimetric inequality</a> states that,=
 for a closed curve of length <i>L</i> (so the region it encloses has <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perimeter" title=3D"Perimeter">perimete=
r</a> <i>L</i>) and for area <i>A</i> of the region that it encloses,
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e 4\pi A\leq L^{2},}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>4</mn>
        <mi>=CF=80<!-- =CF=80 --></mi>
        <mi>A</mi>
        <mo>=E2=89=A4<!-- =E2=89=A4 --></mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>L</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 4\pi A\leq L^=
{2},}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/dd8bd2c0d6a1230d3672a79f0974b1488aa89df1" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:10.62ex; height:3.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 4\p=
i A\leq L^{2},}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>and  equality holds if and only if the curve is a <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Circle" title=3D"Circle">circle</a>. Thus a circle has t=
he largest area of any closed figure with a given perimeter.
</p><p>At the other extreme, a figure with given perimeter <i>L</i> could h=
ave an arbitrarily small area, as illustrated by a <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Rhombus" title=3D"Rhombus">rhombus</a> that is "tipped ove=
r" arbitrarily far so that two of its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Angle" title=3D"Angle">angles</a> are arbitrarily close to 0=C2=B0 and =
the other two are arbitrarily close to 180=C2=B0.
</p><p>For a circle, the ratio of the area to the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Circumference" title=3D"Circumference">circumference</a> (t=
he term for the perimeter of a circle) equals half the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radius" title=3D"Radius">radius</a> <i>r</i>. This can=
 be seen from the area formula <i>=CF=80r</i><sup>2</sup> and the circumfer=
ence formula 2<i>=CF=80r</i>.
</p><p>The area of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_polyg=
on" title=3D"Regular polygon">regular polygon</a> is half its perimeter tim=
es the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apothem" title=3D"Apothem">=
apothem</a> (where the apothem is the distance from the center to the neare=
st point on any side).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Fractals">Fractals</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArea&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit section: Fractals"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Doubling the edge lengths of a polygon multiplies its area by four, whic=
h is two (the ratio of the new to the old side length) raised to the power =
of two (the dimension of the space the polygon resides in). But if the one-=
dimensional lengths of a  <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractal"=
 title=3D"Fractal">fractal</a> drawn in two dimensions are all doubled, the=
 spatial content of the fractal scales by a power of two that is not necess=
arily an integer. This power is called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Fractal_dimension" title=3D"Fractal dimension">fractal dimension</=
a> of the fractal.
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Mandelbrot1983_33-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-Mandelbrot1983-33"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Area_bisectors">Area bisect=
ors</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArea&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" title=3D"Edit section: Area bisectors"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bisection#Area_bisec=
tors_and_perimeter_bisectors" title=3D"Bisection">Bisection =C2=A7&nbsp;Are=
a bisectors and perimeter bisectors</a></div>
<p>There are an infinitude of lines that bisect the area of a triangle. Thr=
ee of them are the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Median_(triangl=
e)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Median (triangle)">medians</a> of the tr=
iangle (which connect the sides' midpoints with the opposite vertices), and=
 these are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concurrent_lines" title=
=3D"Concurrent lines">concurrent</a> at the triangle's <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centroid" title=3D"Centroid">centroid</a>; indeed, the=
y are the only area bisectors that go through the centroid. Any line throug=
h a triangle that splits both the triangle's area and its perimeter in half=
 goes through the triangle's incenter (the center of its <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Incircle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Incircle">i=
ncircle</a>). There are either one, two, or three of these for any given tr=
iangle.
</p><p>Any line through the midpoint of a parallelogram bisects the area.
</p><p>All area bisectors of a circle or other ellipse go through the cente=
r, and any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chord_(geometry)" title=
=3D"Chord (geometry)">chords</a> through the center bisect the area. In the=
 case of a circle they are the diameters of the circle.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Optimization">Optimization<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArea&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit section: Optimization"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Given a wire contour, the surface of least area spanning ("filling") it =
is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minimal_surface" title=3D"Min=
imal surface">minimal surface</a>.  Familiar examples include <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soap_bubble" title=3D"Soap bubble">soap bubbles=
</a>.
</p><p>The question of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Filling=
_area_conjecture" title=3D"Filling area conjecture">filling area</a> of the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riemannian_circle" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Riemannian circle">Riemannian circle</a> remains open.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Area#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The circle has the largest area of any two-dimensional object having=
 the same perimeter.
</p><p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyclic_polygon" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Cyclic polygon">cyclic polygon</a> (one inscribed in =
a circle) has the largest area of any polygon with a given number of sides =
of the same lengths.
</p><p>A version of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isoperimet=
ric_inequality" title=3D"Isoperimetric inequality">isoperimetric inequality=
</a> for triangles states that the triangle of greatest area among all thos=
e with a given perimeter is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equila=
teral" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Equilateral">equilateral</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Chakerian_35-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-Chakerian-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The triangle of largest area of all those inscribed in a given circl=
e is equilateral; and the triangle of smallest area of all those circumscri=
bed around a given circle is equilateral.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-36"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p><p>The ratio of the area of the incircle to the area of an equilateral =
triangle, <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span cl=
ass=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;=
"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displayst=
yle {\frac {\pi }{3{\sqrt {3}}}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mi>=CF=80<!-- =CF=80 --></mi>
            <mrow>
              <mn>3</mn>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <msqrt>
                  <mn>3</mn>
                </msqrt>
              </mrow>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\frac {\pi }=
{3{\sqrt {3}}}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/9e87580f1fcf9c9b18a8e4a5d9261491e79b8bf8" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.838ex; width:5.097ex; height:5.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\f=
rac {\pi }{3{\sqrt {3}}}}}"></span>, is larger than that of any non-equilat=
eral triangle.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The ratio of the area to the square of the perimeter of an equilater=
al triangle, <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span=
 class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: no=
ne;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displa=
ystyle {\frac {1}{12{\sqrt {3}}}},}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mn>1</mn>
            <mrow>
              <mn>12</mn>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <msqrt>
                  <mn>3</mn>
                </msqrt>
              </mrow>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\frac {1}{12=
{\sqrt {3}}}},}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/844409c74d8d57e537c55a4c22aeea1a25ecd65a" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.838ex; width:6.906ex; height:6.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\f=
rac {1}{12{\sqrt {3}}}},}"></span> is larger than that for any other triang=
le.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Chakerian_35-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#cite_note-Chakerian-35"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
